# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ethics-of-eating-meat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Conversations regarding the **ethics of eating meat** are focused on whether or not it is moral to eat non-human animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] People who abstain from eating meat are generally known as vegetarians and people who avoid all animal by-products are known as vegans.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] They avoid meat for a variety of reasons, including taste preference, animal welfare, ethical reasons, religion, the environmental impact of meat production (*environmental vegetarianism*), health considerations, and antimicrobial resistance.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Individuals who promote meat consumption do so for a number of reasons, such as health, cultural traditions, religious beliefs, and scientific arguments that support the practice.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The majority of the world’s health and dietetics associations state that a well-planned vegetarian or vegan diet can be nutritionally adequate for all stages of life.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A common argument used in the animal rights movement is the argument from marginal cases, asserting that non-human animals should have the moral status similar to that of marginal case human beings such as human infants, the senile, the comatose, and the cognitively disabled.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Proponents argue that there are no morally relevant traits that these marginal humans possess that animals lack.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In addition to flesh, vegans also abstain from other animal products, such as dairy products, honey and eggs, for similar reasons.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] "Ethical omnivores" are individuals who object to the practices underlying the production of meat, as opposed to the act of consuming meat itself.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] They do not believe animals deserve the right not to be killed and treated as commodities, but rather, they believe it is permissible to kill them as long as welfare is taken into account.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In this respect, many people who abstain from certain kinds of meat eating and animal products do not take issue with meat consumption in general, provided that the meat and animal products are produced in a specific manner.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Ethical omnivores may object to rearing animals for meat in factory farms, killing animals in ways that cause pain, and feeding animals unnecessary antibiotics or hormones.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] To this end, they may avoid meats such as veal, foie gras, meat from animals that were not free range, animals that were fed antibiotics or hormones, etc.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In a 2014 survey of 406 US philosophy professors, approximately 60% of ethicists and 45% of non-ethicist philosophers said it was at least somewhat "morally bad" to eat meat from mammals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A 2020 survey of 1,812 published English-language philosophers found that 48% said it was permissible to eat animals in ordinary circumstances, while 45% said it was not.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The *World Scientists' Warning to Humanity* (2017), the most co-signed scientific journal article in history, called (among other things) for a transition to plant-based diets in order to combat climate change.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Conversations regarding the ethics of meat eating have been ongoing for thousands of years, possibly longer.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Pythagoras, a Greek mathematician and philosopher who lived during the 6th century BC, made the case against eating animals on grounds of their having souls like humans.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Taking an entirely different approach, Plato, an Athenian philosopher who lived during the 4th century BC, argued that meat is a luxury item that requires a lot of land to procure.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] As a result, he stated that the unmoderated consumption of meat would lead to conflict over land and, ultimately, an unsustainable society.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Plutarch, a Middle Platonist philosopher and vegetarian, dedicated a section of his *Moralia* to the consumption of animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] He argued that flesh-eating is not a necessity but a luxury rooted in gluttony and desensitization to violence.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] He emphasized the cruelty of killing animals for pleasure, contrasting it with the simplicity and sufficiency of plant-based sustenance.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Rene Descartes, a 17th-century French philosopher, mathematician, and scientist, disagreed with the aforementioned stances.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] He argued that animals were not conscious.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] As a result, he asserted that there is nothing ethically wrong with consuming meat or causing animals physical pain.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Immanuel Kant also argued that there is nothing ethically wrong with meat consumption.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] He claimed that it was personhood that distinguished humans from animals and that, since animals are not actual persons, there was nothing wrong with killing or consuming them.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Peter Singer, a Princeton University and University of Melbourne professor and pioneer of the animal liberation movement, argues that, because non-human animals feel, they should be treated according to utilitarian ethics.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In his ethical philosophy of what it is to be a "person", Singer ultimately argues that livestock animals feel enough to deserve better treatment than they receive.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Singer's work has since been widely built upon by philosophers who agree and who do not.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] His essential philosophies have been largely adopted by animal rights advocates as well as by ethical vegetarians and vegans.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Many other modern thinkers have questioned the morality not only of the double standard underlying speciesism but also the double standard underlying the fact that people support treatment of cows, pigs, and chickens in ways that they would never allow with pet dogs, cats, or birds.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Nick Zangwill, a British philosopher and honorary research professor at University College London and Lincoln University, disagrees with Singer's conclusions about the moral necessity of not eating meat.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In *Our Moral Duty to Eat Meat*, which was published by Cambridge University Press, Zangwill argues that the existence of domesticated animals depends on the practice of eating them, and that meat eating has historically benefitted many millions of animals and given them good lives.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Consequently, he claims that eating non-human animal meat is not merely permissible but also good for many millions of animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] However, Zangwill clarifies that this argument does not apply to factory farm animals, as they do not have good lives.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Thus, when he speaks of meat eating being justified, he means only meat from animals that overall have a good life.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Ethical vegetarians say that the reasons for not hurting or killing animals are similar to the reasons for not hurting or killing humans.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] They argue that killing an animal, like killing a human, can only be justified in extreme circumstances, such as when one's life is threatened.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Consuming a living creature just for its taste, for convenience, or out of habit is not justifiable.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Some ethicists have added that humans, unlike other animals, are morally conscious of their behavior and have a choice; this is why there are laws governing human behavior, and why it is subject to moral standards.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Ethical vegetarian concerns have become more widespread in developed countries, particularly because of the spread of factory farming, more open and graphic documentation of what human meat-eating entails for the animal, and environmental consciousness.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Reducing the worldwide massive food waste would also contribute to reduce meat waste and therefore save animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Some have described unequal treatment of humans and animals as a form of speciesism such as anthropocentrism or human-centeredness.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Val Plumwood (1993, 1996) has argued that anthropocentrism plays a role in green theory that is analogous to androcentrism in feminist theory and ethnocentrism in anti-racist theory.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Plumwood calls human-centredness "anthropocentrism" to emphasize this parallel.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] By analogy with racism and sexism, Melanie Joy has dubbed meat-eating "carnism".
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The animal rights movement seeks an end to the rigid moral and legal distinction drawn between human and non-human animals, an end to the status of animals as property, and an end to their use in the research, food, clothing, and entertainment industries.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Jane Goodall, an ethologist, stated in the 2009 book *The Inner World of Farm Animals* that "farm animals feel pleasure and sadness, excitement and resentment, depression, fear, and pain.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Eugene Linden, author of *The Parrot's Lament*, suggests that many examples of animal behavior and intelligence seem to indicate both emotion and a level of consciousness that we would normally ascribe only to our own species.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Philosophers Peter Singer (Princeton), Jeff McMahan (Oxford) and others also counter that the issue is not one of consciousness, but of sentience.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A related argument revolves around non-human organisms' ability to feel pain.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] If animals could be shown to suffer, as humans do, then many of the arguments against human suffering could be extended to animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] One such reaction is transmarginal inhibition, a phenomenon observed in humans and some animals akin to mental breakdown.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Various programs operate around the world that promote the notion that animals raised for food can be treated humanely.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Some spokespeople for the factory farming industry argue that the animals are better off in total confinement.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In response, animal welfare advocates ask for evidence that any factory-bred animal is better off caged than free.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Farm Sanctuary argues that commodifying and slaughtering animals is incompatible with the definition of "humane".
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Animal ethicists such as Gary Francione have argued that reducing animal suffering is not enough; it needs to be made illegal and abolished.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] David Benatar contends that of the 63 billion land animals killed annually to provide humans with meat products, the vast majority of them die painful and stressful deaths.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Critics of ethical vegetarianism say that there is no agreement on where to draw the line between organisms that can and cannot feel.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] There are some who argue that, although only suffering animals feel anguish, plants, like all organisms, have evolved mechanisms for survival.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] No living organism can be described as "wanting" to die for another organism's sustenance.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Supporters of ethical vegetarianism argue that support for plant rights obligates abstaining from meat, due to the use of plants to rear animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] For example, the feed conversion ratio for beef can require 4.5–7.5 kg of plant food to be used to produce 1 kg of beef.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] PETA states that "Whether it can be proved that plants experience pain or not, vegan foods are the compassionate choice because they require the deaths of fewer plants *and* animals." Singer observed that the ethical argument for vegetarianism may not apply to all non-vegetarian food.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] For example, any arguments against causing pain to animals would not apply to animals that do not feel pain.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] It has also often been noted that, while it takes a lot more grain to feed some animals such as cows for human consumption than it takes to feed a human directly, not all animals consume land plants (or other animals that consume land plants).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] For example, oysters consume underwater plankton and algae.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] When people choose to do things about which they are ambivalent and which they would have difficulty justifying, they experience a state of cognitive dissonance, which can lead to rationalization, denial, or even self-deception.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] For example, a 2011 experiment found that, when the harm that their meat-eating causes animals is explicitly brought to people's attention, they tend to rate those animals as possessing fewer mental capacities compared to when the harm is not brought to their attention.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This is especially evident when people expect to eat meat in the near future.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Such denial makes it less uncomfortable for people to eat animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The data suggest that people who consume meat go to great lengths to try to resolve these moral inconsistencies between their beliefs and behaviour by adjusting their beliefs about what animals are capable of feeling.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This perception can lead to paradoxical conclusions about the ethics and comfort involved in preferring certain types of meat over others.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] For example, venison or meat from a wild deer generally has a much higher nutritional quality and a much lower carbon footprint than meat from domestically-raised animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Many ethical vegetarians and ethical meat-eaters argue that it is behaviour rather than supporting beliefs that should be adjusted.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Some people choose to not eat meat for environmental reasons.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] It accounts also for over 8% of global human water use.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Livestock production is the biggest human use of land, and it accounts for around 25% of the global land surface, or two-thirds of all agricultural land.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] It is probably the leading player in biodiversity loss, as it causes deforestation, land degradation, pollution, climate change, and overfishing.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A 2017 study by the World Wildlife Fund found that 60% of biodiversity loss can be attributed to the vast scale of feed crop cultivation needed to rear tens of billions of farm animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Livestock is also responsible for at least 20% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions, which are the main cause of the current climate change.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This is due to feed production, enteric fermentation from ruminants, manure storage and processing, and transportation of animal products.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The greenhouse gas emissions from livestock production greatly exceeds the greenhouse gas emissions of any other human activity.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Some authors argue that by far the best thing we can do to slow climate change is a global shift towards a vegetarian or vegan diet.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A 2017 study published in the journal *Carbon Balance and Management* found animal agriculture's global methane emissions are 11% higher than previously estimated.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In November 2017, 15,364 world scientists signed a warning to humanity calling for, among other things, "promoting dietary shifts towards mostly plant-based foods." A 2019 report in *The Lancet* recommended that global meat consumption be reduced by 50 percent to mitigate climate change.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Many developing countries, including China and India, are moving away from traditional plant-based diets to more meat-intensive diets as the result of modernization and globalization, which has facilitated the spread of Western consumer cultures around the world.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Around 166 to over 200 billion land and aquatic animals are consumed by the global population of over 8 billion every year, and meat consumption is projected to more than double by 2050 as the population grows to over 9 billion.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A 2018 study published in *Science* states that meat consumption could rise by as much as 76% by 2050 as the result of human population growth and rising affluence, which will increase greenhouse gas emissions and further reduce biodiversity.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Animals that feed on grain or rely on grazing require more water than grain crops.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Producing 1 kg (2.2 lb) of meat requires up to 15,000 liters of water.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] According to the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), growing crops for farm animals requires nearly half of the US water supply and 80% of its agricultural land.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Animals raised for food in the US consume 90% of the soy crop, 80% of the corn crop, and 70% of its grain.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] However, where an extensive farming system (as opposed to a feedlot) is used, some water and nutrients are returned to the soil to provide a benefit to the pasture.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This cycling and processing of water and nutrients is less prevalent in most plant production systems, so may bring the efficiency rate of animal production closer to the efficiency of plant based agricultural systems.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In tracking food animal production from the feed through to the dinner table, the inefficiencies of meat, milk, and egg production range from a 4:1 energy input to protein output ratio up to 54:1.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The result is that producing animal-based food is typically much less efficient than the harvesting of grains, vegetables, legumes, seeds, and fruits.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] There are also environmentalist arguments in favor of the morality of eating meat.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] One such line of argument holds that sentience and individual welfare are less important to morality than the greater ecological good.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Following environmentalist Aldo Leopold's principle that the sole criterion for morality is preserving the "integrity, stability and beauty of the biotic community", this position asserts that sustainable hunting and animal agriculture are environmentally healthy and therefore good.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Jay Bost, an agroecologist and winner of *The New York Times*' essay contest on the ethics of eating meat, supports meat consumption, arguing that "eating meat raised in specific circumstances is ethical; eating meat raised in other circumstances is unethical" in regard to environmental usage.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] He proposes that if "ethical is defined as living in the most ecologically benign way, then in fairly specific circumstances, of which each eater must educate himself, eating meat is ethical." The specific circumstances he mentions include using animals to cycle nutrients and convert sun to food.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Buddhist vegetarianism has similar strictures against hurting animals.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The actual practices of Hindus and Buddhists vary according to their community and according to regional traditions.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Jains are especially rigorous about not harming sentient organisms.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Islamic Law and Judaism have dietary guidelines called Halal and Kashrut, respectively.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In Judaism, meat that may be consumed according to *halakha* (Jewish law) is termed *kosher*; meat that is not compliant with Jewish law is called *treif*.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Causing unnecessary pain to animals is prohibited by the principle of tza'ar ba'alei chayim.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] While it is neither required nor prohibited for Jews to eat meat, a number of medieval scholars of Judaism, such as Joseph Albo and Isaac Arama, regard vegetarianism as a moral ideal.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Similarly, Islamic dietary laws permit the consumption of certain animals at the condition that their meat is not obtained through prohibited methods of slaughtering (ex: strangling, beaten to death, etc.), along with adherence to other restrictions.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Meat obtained through prohibited methods of slaughtering is considered haram.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In Christianity as practised by members of Eastern Orthodox Church, Roman Catholic Church, Greek Catholic Church, and others, it is prohibited to eat meat in times of fasting.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] There are also Christian monastic orders that practice vegetarianism.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Shinto has a concept of kegare, which means a state of pollution and defilement, and traditionally eating animals is thought to be one of them.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Eating animals having more legs is thought to be worse (*i.e.*, eating mammals is worse than eating chickens or fish).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This concept leads to discrimination against slaughtermen and people who work with leather, who are called burakumin.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Shinran, the founder of the Buddhist sect Jōdo Shinshū, taught that lower class who had to kill beings could enter nirvana even though killing animals was thought to be immoral.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Thus, some opponents of ethical vegetarianism argue that the analogy between killing animals and killing people is misleading.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] For example, Hsiao (2015) compares the moral severity of harming animals to that of picking a flower or introducing malware into a computer.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Others have argued that humans are capable of culture, innovation, and the sublimation of instinct in order to act in an ethical manner while animals are not, and so are unequal to humans on a moral level.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This does not excuse cruelty, but it implies animals are not morally equivalent to humans and do not possess the rights a human has.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] The precise definition of a moral community is not simple, but Hsiao defines membership by the ability to know one's own good and that of other members, and to be able to grasp this in the abstract.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] He claims that non-human animals do not meet this standard.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Benjamin Franklin describes his conversion to vegetarianism in chapter one of his autobiography but he describes why he periodically ceased vegetarianism in his later life.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Opponents of eating meat argue that meat production foments zoonotic diseases, leading to increased pandemics, a claim backed up by a 2020 United Nations report.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] A 2017 paper stated that "An estimated 60% of known infectious diseases and up to 75% of new or emerging infectious diseases are zoonotic in origin" and that "It is estimated that zoonoses are responsible for 2.5 billion cases of human illness and 2.7 million human deaths worldwide each year".
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Meat production often involves the usage of antibiotics on livestock, fueling antibiotic resistance.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Antibiotic resistance has been argued to be as big of a threat as climate change.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Critics of this line of reasoning state that while widespread adoption of vegan diets would reduce the fomenting of zoonotic diseases, antibiotic resistance, and pandemics, vegan food production still often involves antibiotics and does not eliminate these problems altogether.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Davis, a professor of animal science at Oregon State University, argues that the least harm principle does not require giving up all meat.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Davis states that a diet containing beef from grass-fed ruminants such as cattle would kill fewer animals than a vegetarian diet, particularly when one takes into account animals killed by agriculture.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] This conclusion has been criticized by Jason Gaverick Matheny (founder of *in vitro* meat organization New Harvest) because it calculates the number of animals killed per acre (instead of per consumer).
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Matheny says that, when the numbers are adjusted, Davis' argument shows veganism as perpetrating the least harm.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Davis' argument has also been criticized by Andy Lamey for being based on only two studies that may not represent commercial agricultural practices.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] When differentiating between animals killed by farm machinery and those killed by other animals, he says that the studies again show veganism to do the "least harm".
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] One of the main differences between a vegan and a typical vegetarian diet is the avoidance of eggs, honey and dairy products such as milk, cheese, butter, and yogurt.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Ethical vegans do not consume dairy or eggs because of the exploitation and slaughter of animals in the dairy and egg industries and because of the environmental effect of dairy production.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] To produce milk from dairy cattle, most calves are separated from their mothers soon after birth (called cow-calf separation) and fed milk replacement in order to retain the cows' milk for human consumption.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Animal welfare advocates point out that this breaks the natural bond between the mother and her calf.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Unwanted male calves are either slaughtered at birth or sent for veal production.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] To prolong lactation, dairy cows are almost permanently kept pregnant through artificial insemination.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Although cows' natural life expectancy is about twenty years, after about five years the cows' milk production has dropped; they are then considered "spent" and are sent to slaughter for meat and leather.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] Battery cages are the predominant form of housing for egg laying hens worldwide; these cages reduce aggression and cannibalism among hens, but are barren, restrict movement, and increase rates of osteoporosis.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] In these systems and in free-range egg production, unwanted male chicks are culled and killed at birth during the process of securing a further generation of egg-laying hens.
[src:ethics-of-eating-meat/ethics-of-eating-meat] It is estimated that an average consumer of eggs who eats 200 eggs per year for 70 years of his or her life is responsible for the deaths of 140 birds, and that an average consumer of milk who drinks 190 kg (420 lb) per year for 70 years is responsible for the deaths of 2.5 cows.
